---

<ToolLayout
  title="Image Blur & Pixelate Tool - Privacy Protection | Webutilbox"
  description="Blur or pixelate images online for privacy or creative effects. Control blur intensity and pixelation size. Free browser-based image blur tool."
  canonical={canonical}
  ogImage="https://webutilbox.com/assets/og/og-image-tools.svg"
  keywords="blur image, pixelate image, censor photo, hide face, privacy tool, redact image"
  h1="🌫️ Image Blur & Pixelate Tool"
  subtitle="Protect privacy by blurring or pixelating sensitive areas in images."
  lastUpdated=""
  shareText="Free%20online%20Image%20Blur%20%26%20Pixelate%20Tool%20on%20Webutilbox.%20Privacy-focused%2C%20runs%20100%25%20in%20your%20browser."
  shareUrl={canonical}
  embedUrl={canonical}
  embedTitle="Image Blur & Pixelate Tool - Privacy Protection -- Webutilbox"
  embedHeight={600}
  toolCss={true}
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>

<div class="workspace" style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 15px;">
            <!-- Left: Upload & Canvas -->
            <div>
                <div id="uploadArea">
                    <div style="border: 2px dashed var(--border); border-radius: 8px; padding: 25px; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; transition: all 0.3s;" id="dropZone" onclick="document.getElementById('fileInput').click()">
                        <div style="font-size: 2rem; margin-bottom: 5px;">🖼️</div>
                        <div style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--white); margin-bottom: 3px;">Click to upload or drag & drop image</div>
                        <div style="font-size: 0.7rem; color: var(--gray);">JPG, PNG, WebP</div>
                    </div>
                    <input type="file" id="fileInput" accept="image/*" style="display: none;" onchange="handleFile(this.files[0])">
                </div>

                <!-- Canvas Area -->
                <div id="canvasArea" style="display: none; background: var(--light); border-radius: 8px; padding: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--border); margin-top: 12px;">
                    <div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; margin-bottom: 8px;">
                        <div style="font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gray);">Draw rectangles to blur/pixelate</div>
                        <button onclick="uploadNew()" style="padding: 4px 10px; font-size: 0.7rem; background: var(--primary); border: none; border-radius: 4px; color: white; cursor: pointer;">📤 Upload New</button>
                    </div>
                    <div style="position: relative; display: inline-block; max-width: 100%;">
                        <canvas id="canvas" style="max-width: 100%; border-radius: 6px; display: block; cursor: crosshair; border: 2px solid var(--border);"></canvas>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Right: Controls -->
            <div id="controls" style="display: none;">
                <!-- Effect Type -->
                <div style="margin-bottom: 12px;">
                    <label style="font-size: 0.8rem; margin-bottom: 6px; display: block; color: var(--gray);">Effect Type</label>
                    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 8px;">
                        <button onclick="setEffect('blur')" id="effect-blur" class="active-effect" style="padding: 10px; background: var(--primary); border: none; border-radius: 6px; cursor: pointer; font-size: 0.85rem; color: white; font-weight: 500;">Blur</button>
                        <button onclick="setEffect('pixelate')" id="effect-pixelate" style="padding: 10px; background: var(--dark); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 6px; cursor: pointer; font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--white); font-weight: 500;">Pixelate</button>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Blur Settings -->
                <div id="blur-settings" style="background: var(--light); border-radius: 8px; padding: 12px; margin-bottom: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--border);">
                    <div style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--gray); margin-bottom: 10px;">Blur Settings</div>
                    <div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; margin-bottom: 4px;">
                        <label style="font-size: 0.75rem;">Blur Intensity</label>
                        <span style="font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--primary);" id="blurAmount-val">20px</span>
                    </div>
                    <input type="range" id="blurAmount" min="5" max="50" value="20" oninput="document.getElementById('blurAmount-val').textContent = this.value + 'px'" style="width: 100%;">
                </div>

                <!-- Pixelate Settings -->
                <div id="pixelate-settings" style="display: none; background: var(--light); border-radius: 8px; padding: 12px; margin-bottom: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--border);">
                    <div style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--gray); margin-bottom: 10px;">Pixelate Settings</div>
                    <div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; margin-bottom: 4px;">
                        <label style="font-size: 0.75rem;">Pixel Size</label>
                        <span style="font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--primary);" id="pixelSize-val">15px</span>
                    </div>
                    <input type="range" id="pixelSize" min="5" max="40" value="15" oninput="document.getElementById('pixelSize-val').textContent = this.value + 'px'" style="width: 100%;">
                </div>

                <!-- Instructions -->
                <div style="background: var(--light); border-radius: 8px; padding: 12px; margin-bottom: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--border);">
                    <div style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--gray); margin-bottom: 8px;">Instructions</div>
                    <div style="font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--white); line-height: 1.6;">
                        1. Click and drag on the image to draw rectangles<br>
                        2. Each rectangle will be blurred/pixelated<br>
                        3. Draw multiple areas as needed<br>
                        4. Use "Clear Last" to undo or "Clear All" to reset
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Areas List -->
                <div style="background: var(--light); border-radius: 8px; padding: 12px; margin-bottom: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--border);">
                    <div style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--gray); margin-bottom: 8px;">Censored Areas: <span id="areaCount">0</span></div>
                    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 8px;">
                        <button onclick="clearLast()" style="padding: 8px; background: var(--dark); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 6px; cursor: pointer; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--white);">Clear Last</button>
                        <button onclick="clearAll()" style="padding: 8px; background: var(--dark); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 6px; cursor: pointer; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--white);">Clear All</button>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Download Button -->
                <button onclick="downloadImage()" class="btn btn-success" style="width: 100%; padding: 10px; font-size: 0.95rem;">💾 Download Censored Image</button>
            </div>
        </div>

        
        <!-- Share Bar -->




<script src="/js/image-blur-pixelate.js" defer></script>

<div class="info-section" slot="info">
<h2>Image Blur & Pixelate Tool - Privacy Protection for Your Images</h2>
    <p>The Image Blur &amp; Pixelate tool lets you obscure sensitive areas in images directly in your browser. Hide faces, license plates, personal information, and confidential content before sharing images online or in documents. No software installation needed — everything runs instantly in your browser.</p>

    <h3>What Is the Image Blur &amp; Pixelate Tool?</h3>
    <p>This tool is a browser-based image redaction utility that allows you to draw rectangular regions over any part of an image and apply either a blur or pixelation effect to those regions. It is designed for anyone who needs to protect privacy, comply with data regulations, or simply remove distracting elements from a photo before sharing it publicly. Whether you are a journalist protecting a source, a developer writing documentation, or a social media user respecting others' privacy, this tool gives you a fast and reliable way to redact images without installing any software.</p>
    <p>The blur effect uses a Gaussian-style softening algorithm that smoothly blends pixels together, making the obscured area look naturally out of focus. The pixelation effect reduces the selected region to large visible blocks of color — the classic "mosaic" censorship style you see in news broadcasts and documentary footage. Both methods are highly effective at making the underlying content unreadable to human viewers, and you can adjust the intensity of each effect to match your specific needs.</p>
    <p>Unlike desktop software that requires installation and setup, this tool works entirely within your web browser. You can upload an image, apply multiple blur or pixelate regions, and download the result in seconds. The tool supports JPG, PNG, and WebP formats, and the output is saved as a high-quality PNG to preserve the edits without additional compression artifacts. The full-resolution output ensures that the downloaded image matches the original dimensions exactly, with only the selected regions obscured.</p>

    <h3>Blur and Pixelate Effects</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Draw multiple rectangular regions on a single image — blur or pixelate as many areas as needed in one session, covering faces, text, logos, or any sensitive content.</li>
        <li>Switch between blur and pixelate effects at any time, with adjustable intensity sliders for each effect so you can fine-tune how strongly the content is obscured.</li>
        <li>Real-time preview shows the effect applied to the canvas as you draw, so you can see exactly what the result will look like before downloading.</li>
        <li>Undo the last region or clear all regions with a single click, making it easy to correct mistakes without starting over from scratch.</li>
        <li>Full-resolution output — the downloaded image is processed at the original image dimensions, not the scaled preview size, ensuring maximum quality in the final file.</li>
        <li>Drag-and-drop upload support for a fast, frictionless workflow — simply drag your image file onto the upload area to get started immediately.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>How to Use the Image Blur &amp; Pixelate Tool</h3>
    <p>Getting started is straightforward — just follow these steps to protect sensitive content in your images.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Step 1: Upload your image by clicking the upload area or dragging and dropping a file directly onto the page. Supported formats include JPG, PNG, and WebP.</li>
        <li>Step 2: Choose your effect type — select "Blur" for a smooth, out-of-focus look, or "Pixelate" for the classic mosaic censorship style that creates large colored blocks.</li>
        <li>Step 3: Adjust the intensity slider to control how strongly the effect is applied. For blur, higher values create a stronger obscuring effect. For pixelation, larger pixel sizes make the blocks more prominent and the content less recognizable.</li>
        <li>Step 4: Click and drag on the image canvas to draw a rectangle over the area you want to obscure. You can draw as many rectangles as needed — each one is applied independently, so you can cover multiple faces, license plates, or text fields in a single session.</li>
        <li>Step 5: When satisfied with the result, click "Download Censored Image" to save the processed image to your device at full resolution, ready to share safely.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>When to Blur or Pixelate Images</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Privacy protection on social media — blur faces of people who have not consented to being photographed before posting images publicly on Instagram, Facebook, or Twitter.</li>
        <li>Document redaction — hide account numbers, passwords, addresses, and other sensitive data visible in screenshots before sharing them in support tickets, tutorials, or blog posts.</li>
        <li>License plate obscuring — remove vehicle registration numbers from street-level photos, property listings, travel photography, or dashcam footage before publishing online.</li>
        <li>GDPR and data compliance — anonymize personal data visible in images to comply with privacy regulations when publishing content that includes identifiable individuals or personal information.</li>
        <li>Tutorial and instructional content creation — hide irrelevant UI elements, personal account details, or confidential information in screenshots used for guides, documentation, and training materials.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Getting the Best Effect Results</h3>
    <p>For faces, a blur radius of 15–25px is typically sufficient to make facial features completely unrecognizable. For text such as license plates, addresses, or phone numbers, pixelation often works better than blur because it eliminates the possibility of edge-detection algorithms reconstructing the text from the blurred gradient. Always use the highest intensity setting when dealing with truly sensitive information to ensure the content cannot be recovered.</p>
    <p>When obscuring multiple areas in a single image, work systematically from top to bottom or left to right so you do not accidentally miss any sensitive regions. After applying all your edits, zoom in on the downloaded image to verify that all sensitive content is fully obscured before sharing it. It is easy to miss small details like partial text or a reflected face in a mirror, so a careful review is always worthwhile.</p>
    <p>For highly sensitive information — such as financial data, medical records, or legal documents — consider using a solid black fill rather than blur or pixelation. While blur and pixelation are effective against human viewers, advanced AI reconstruction techniques have shown some ability to recover content from lightly blurred regions. A solid opaque fill provides absolute certainty that the underlying content cannot be recovered by any means.</p>

    

    <h3>Images Processed in Your Browser Only</h3>
    <p>Image processing uses the Canvas API locally. Your images are never uploaded.</p>

            <h3>Frequently Asked Questions</h3>
            <div class="faq-list">
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the difference between blur and pixelate effects?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Blur smooths the image by averaging neighboring pixels, creating a soft, out-of-focus look. Pixelate divides the image into large square blocks and fills each block with a single average color, creating a mosaic or censored appearance. Both are used to obscure sensitive information.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I blur only part of an image?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. Use the selection tool to draw a rectangle over the area you want to blur or pixelate, then apply the effect. The rest of the image remains unchanged. This is useful for redacting faces, license plates, or personal information in screenshots.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is blurring a reliable way to hide sensitive information?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Blur can be partially reversed using AI upscaling tools, especially if the blur is light. For truly sensitive information (passwords, credit card numbers, personal data), use the pixelate effect with a large block size, or use a solid color overlay to completely cover the information.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What blur radius should I use?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>For a subtle depth-of-field effect, use a small radius (2-5px). For clearly obscuring content, use 10-20px or higher. The pixelate block size works similarly — larger blocks = more obscured.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I apply multiple effects to the same image?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. Apply blur to one region, then pixelate another region, and so on. Each operation is applied to the current state of the image, so effects stack. Download the final result when you are done.</p></div>
                </div>
            </div>

